What is Digital Accessibility?

01
On this page
  1. Accessibility is...
  2. Inaccessibility is discrimination in practice, whether intentional or not.
  3. Accessibility for Individuals
  4. Accessibility for Businesses
  5. Accessibility for Society

Let’s start with the definition of digital accessibility:

Digital accessibility refers to the practice of preventing and removing barriers that keep disabled people from accessing, reading, or writing digital content and interacting with online features.

The goal is to eliminate barriers to access.

Early in the development phase, it might involve talking to designers if we catch things that could be problematic. We want to prevent accessibility issues from being shipped as much as possible.

If accessibility issues are found, they should be prioritized and remembered for the next thing your team builds.

It’s all about making products that don’t prevent users from participating.

Accessibility is...

Accessibility is a civil right to participate in society.

It’s not a privilege. It’s not something we’re doing out of charity.

There is a civil and human right to access the internet.

As things go increasingly more online, when someone can’t participate the effect can be drastic.

It's very important that we do not exclude people with disabilities.

With better accessibility, we have more inclusion.

Accessibility is a key part of design.

There’s only so much that can be fixed with code. Accessibility belongs with design, user experience, and all the other parts of the software development lifecycle that come before the coding parts. You can’t shove ingredients into an already baked muffin.

There are analogues between accessibility in digital spaces and accessibility in the architectural features of public and private spaces (”the built environment”). Being an accessibility expert is like being an architect. We need to prioritize structural access that includes disability in design and user experience.

Accessibility is often forgotten.

It is unfortunate that accessibility is often forgotten.

Share information about the importance of accessibility.

We need to keep beating this drum to get more people on board and excited about improving access.

To have good results, we can’t marginalize accessibility and say we’ll do it later.

Accessibility should be a priority from the beginning. It must be part of the requirements for the features we ship.

While managing up can be exhausting and fraught with problems, it’s vital to communicate the importance of accessibility in an organization. Find allies and colleagues who are positioned to advocate with you among your management and leadership teams.

Do what you can.

It’s better than being silent.

Inaccessibility is discrimination in practice, whether intentional or not.

It’s not uncommon for organizations to see accessibility as a “nice to have” or say “that’s not our audience.” But real talk:

If accessibility is marginalized, it creates a self-perpetuating culture of discrimination.

When your application doesn’t have keyboard support or support a screen reader, someone with a disability will be excluded.

So is it that people with disabilities aren’t your customers? Or are they prevented from signing up to use your products and services, or apply for a job on your team?

This is why marginalization of accessibility can be discriminatory.

A lot of people don’t want to be that way. Yet we work in systems where decisions are often out of our control. We have to get real about what’s at stake and sometimes using words like discrimination or ableism can get people to pay more attention.

Once we’re aware, we can have a better impact.

Accessibility for Individuals

Accessibility is important for independence.

Whether it’s using an ATM in the physical space or a banking application in digital space, accessibility allows people with disabilities to do their banking and move on with their day without relying on someone else for help.

In inaccessible scenarios of the ATM & banking website examples, a disabled person would have to share their private account information with someone else.

This has implications for privacy and security that can be avoided through accessible interfaces. It’s also why talking ATMs were introduced in the 1990s.

Accessibility means that individuals can apply for and accept jobs. If the job application form on a company’s website is not accessible, they have effectively filtered out people with disabilities. Friction can also be encountered on the job if the tools used by the team are inaccessible.

Accessibility means individuals with disabilities can feel included and connected.

In many countries, disabled people are protected by civil rights legislation. We’ll discuss more about the legal situation later.

Accessibility for Businesses

Individually we can understand the importance of accessibility, but getting a business on board can sometimes be a different challenge.

Many businesses will use “that’s not our customer” as an excuse for not prioritizing accessibility. But if a business website isn’t usable then they can’t be.

An inaccessible product means leaving revenue on the table from disabled people with money to spend.

The impact of accessibility can be seen on the internal side of the business as well.

Hiring individuals with disabilities leads to better products, as first-hand experiences and feedback inform the design and development process. Building things accessibly from the beginning helps avoid costly rework later. Including an accessibility statement and inviting feedback are great ways to continuously improve.

With an accessible product or service, businesses can highlight the work they’ve done. By highlighting legitimate access wins in corporate DEI reports, businesses can also stand out and gain more customers.

And again, the legal considerations are important for businesses to be aware of.

Being proactive with accessibility can avoid costly lawsuits later. It can also help to expand business into government and educational sectors where accessibility is a legal requirement.

Some businesses try to avoid lawsuits by being proactive with accessibility. Other organizations are reactively responding to lawsuits. I've worked with organizations in both positions. Being proactive gives companies more of an opportunity to be innovative when creating accessible digital experiences instead of chasing compliance. Unfortunately, legal risk is often a motivator to getting actual movement on accessibility from stakeholders who are juggling multiple priorities. I don't love it but it's part of the deal, especially in the United States. And it is still a good thing that civil rights laws exist to require access to people with disabilities.

Accessibility for Society

Whether it’s through physical considerations like curb cuts and elevators or using plain language and creating intuitive user interfaces, accessibility leads to a better quality of life.

Accessibility can help reduce social isolation and improve mental health for people with disabilities.

Being able to participate and not be excluded creates opportunities.

If processes and learning materials are accessible, education is more available and people can become more productive with their tools. This leads to successful careers that benefit both the individual and their employer, which in turn impacts society and the economy at large.

When accessibility is a priority, everyone benefits.

To read more, check out “Development and implementation of a framework for estimating the economic benefits of an accessible and inclusive society” from the journal of Equality, Diversity and Inclusion.
